    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_03_30_page01.jpg"/>
                <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
                <opener>
                    <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                        <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>31 Harley S[superscript]t[/superscript]
                        <date when="1816-08-04"/>March 30[superscript]th[/superscript] 1819</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p> My dearest mother, your <choice><orig>cal-<lb/>
                    -culations</orig><reg>calculations</reg></choice> were so <choice><orig>admira<lb/>
                        bly</orig><reg>admirably</reg></choice> just that your letter was<lb/>
                    put into our hands five<lb/>
                    minutes after we had arrived<lb/>
                    at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HopeX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi></persName>Hopes just when we<lb/>
                    had run up to our <hi rend="underline">attics</hi><lb/>
                    to take off our pelisses &amp; unpack<lb/>
                    before we saw <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HopeX2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi></persName>. Hopes or<lb/>
                    any body -- Most happy were<lb/>
                    we to devour it in our snugs<lb/></p>
                    
                <p> -- <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1">Lady E Whitbreads</persName> <choice><orig>kind-<lb/>
                    ness</orig><reg>kindness</reg></choice> to us went on increasing<lb/>
                    to the very last. Two minutes<lb/>
                    before we went away she<lb/>
                    took me into her own room<lb/>
                    &amp; begged that when we have<lb/>
                    completely finished all our<lb/>
                    visits &amp; all that we want to<lb/>
                    do in Town &amp; in short when<lb/>
                    we are on our road <choice><orig>home-<lb/>
                        wards</orig><reg>homewards</reg></choice> we should come to her<lb/></p>
                    
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_03_30_page02.jpg"/>
                    
                 <p>on our way &amp; repose with<lb/>
                     her for 3 or 4 quiet days<lb/>
                     "and I will take care to<lb/>
                     have my brother here for<lb/>
                     you that you may introduce<lb/>
                     to him your dear little<lb/>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1">Francis</persName> -- the most intelligent<lb/>
                     agreeable little boy I ever<lb/>
                     saw"<lb/></p>
                    
                 <p><persName ref="./Personography.xml#GreyE1">Old Lady Gray</persName> came in<lb/>
                     with 4 of her grand children<lb/>
                     just afterwards to introduce<lb/>
                     to them fine <del>children</del> - boys<lb/>
                     but I should prefer <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1">Francis</persName><lb/>
                     to any of them.<lb/></p>
                    
                <p><persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1">Lady E W</persName> expressed the kindest<lb/>
                    and I am sure most sincere<lb/>
                    interest about <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> &amp; her<lb/>
                    affairs - She is in some points<lb/>
                    of her character or temper<lb/>
                    very like my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtM1">aunt Ruxton</persName><lb/>
                    - as ardent - as impatient<lb/>
                    to have what she wishes <choice><orig>de-<lb/>
                        cided</orig><reg>decided</reg></choice> - and instantly -<lb/>
                    
                    She spoke however very<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_03_30_page03.jpg"/>
                    
                    reasonably in <hi rend="underline">summing</hi> up<lb/>
                    &amp; in her charge to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> at<lb/>
                    last to decide quite for her,<lb/>
                    self - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1">Lady EW's</persName> <hi rend="underline">last</hi> opinion<lb/>
                    was favorable to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL2">LW</persName> in every<lb/>
                    respect except wishing him<lb/>
                    to be the husband of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName><lb/>
                    - who as she justly thinks<lb/>
                    deserves a superior person<lb/>
                    - She was very much struck<lb/>
                    with his self command &amp;<lb/>
                    his honorable conduct toward<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">F</persName> in company - and with<lb/>
                    his good temper - and (like<lb/>
                    my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtM1">aunt Ruxton</persName>) his <choice><orig>man<lb/>
                        ner</orig><reg>manner</reg></choice> of coming into the room<lb/>
                    the last evening made a<lb/>
                    great impression in his favor<lb/>
                    "Far from vulgar it was<lb/>
                    really quite gentlemanlike<lb/>
                    &amp; interesting - my daughter<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ShawE1">Emma</persName> observed that she never<lb/>
                    saw a man more in love"<lb/></p>
                    
                <p> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1">Lady E W</persName> has never <del>allowed</del><lb/>
                    told any body what we have told her<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_03_30_page04.jpg"/>
                    
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">- Fanny</persName> wanted to decide the<lb/>
                    matter finally <unclear>in</unclear> the negative<lb/>
                    but both her uncle <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName><lb/>
                    &amp; I separately consulted agreed<lb/>
                    in advising her not to do so<lb/>
                    at present - to take more time<lb/>
                    - for she may be now under<lb/>
                    the influence of impressions<lb/>
                    which will pass away: She<lb/>
                    has seen brilliant &amp; highly<lb/>
                    cultivated society. She is not<lb/>
                    to pass her life in this high<lb/>
                    London nor would it be <choice><orig>de-<lb/>
                        sireable</orig><reg>desireable</reg></choice> if it were possible.<lb/>
                    She is to consider whether he<lb/>
                    has the qualifications that<lb/>
                    will make her happy in the<lb/>
                    situation in which she is likely<lb/>
                    to live - she had better I think<lb/>
                    wait longer to judge of her<lb/>
                    own feelings which have <choice><orig>cer-<lb/>
                        tainly</orig><reg>certainly</reg></choice> changed much since<lb/>
                    last year &amp; I may say within<lb/>
                    this month in consequence<lb/>
                    of new comparisons .<lb/></p>
                    
                    <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_03_30_page05.jpg"/>
                    
               <p>  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HopeX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi></persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HopeX2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Hopes</persName> house will<lb/>
                   show her a brilliant panorama<lb/>
                   - For the first time <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HopeX2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> H</persName> had<lb/>
                   <del>a din</del> an evening party last<lb/>
                   night - at dinner with we had <add><persName ref="./Personography.xml#FansC1">Miss C Fanshawe</persName></add><lb/>
                   <add><persName ref="./Personography.xml#HopeH1">Mr. Harry Hope</persName></add> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CockC1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Cockerell</persName> (too fine) <persName>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>Moore</persName><lb/>
                   son of the Archbishop of Canterbury<lb/>
                   fine too but with excellent<lb/>
                   conversation - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HammX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>Hammersley</persName> -- <add>well informed</add><lb/>
                   <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HamiW1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>Hamilton</persName> under secretary<lb/>
                   of state - very agreeable &amp; unaffected<lb/>
                   - In the evening <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ClarX1">Lady Clare</persName><lb/>
                   - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LindC1"></persName>- <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BurrX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi><lb/>
                       Burrowes M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Hope's sister</persName> -<lb/>
                   <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GlenS1">Lord Glenbervie</persName> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FansX1">Miss Fanshaw</persName><lb/>
                   &amp; several other figures whose<lb/>
                   names I cannot recollect<lb/></p>
                    
                <p><persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Ho</persName> looked very<lb/>
                    pretty. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">F</persName> in white gauze - pink<lb/>
                    gauze <del>turban</del>hand<hi rend="superscript">k</hi> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Ho</persName> - Scotch<lb/>
                    muslin - very pretty little roses in<lb/>
                    hair - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HopeX2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Hope</persName> paid me many<lb/>
                    compliments about <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny's</persName><lb/>
                    beauty &amp; I kept saying she had<lb/>
                    no pretensions to <hi rend="underline">beauty</hi> &amp;<lb/>
                    She asked most kindly for you.</p><lb/>
                    
                <p>  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HopeP1">Mr. <add>Phillip</add>Hope's</persName> brother has given<lb/>
                    him his fine collection of Flemish<lb/>
                    <hi rend="superscript">pictures - the pictures are</hi>are<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_03_30_page06.jpg"/>
                    
                    now piled seven deep in the<lb/>
                    gallery or passage leading to<lb/>
                    our bedchamber with their<lb/>
                    faces to the wall. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HopeX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>Hope</persName><lb/>
                    has built a gallery on purpose<lb/>
                    for them -<lb/></p>
                    
                <p>  This day <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DarnJ1">Lord</persName>&amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DarnE1">Lady</persName> Darnley<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JersG1">Lord</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JersS1">Lady</persName> Jersey - &amp; I forget<lb/>
                    who - and there is to be a<lb/>
                    small party in the evening<lb/>
                    I am glad <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fan</persName> will see all<lb/>
                    this - I have promised to come<lb/>
                    for an hour every day to<lb/>
                    <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Harley-Street_ENK">Harley S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>.</placeName> to let her make her<lb/>
                    own comparisons - All I<lb/>
                    can do is to do nothing at all<lb/>
                    in some situations as Colbert<lb/>
                    found the most difficult<lb/>
                    thing in the world<lb/></p>
                    
                <p>   <persName ref="./Personography#SneyX1">Sneyd</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ExxxX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>E</persName> are at peace<lb/>
                    with me &amp; I have asked <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HopeX2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi><lb/>
                        Hope</persName> to ask them both there<lb/>
                    this eve<hi rend="superscript">g</hi><lb/>
                    Little dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Francis</persName> spent<lb/>
                    saturday &amp; sunday at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Grove-House-Kensington-Gore_ENK">Grove<lb/>
                        house</placeName> with us &amp; I sent him<lb/>
                    home in a hackney coach<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="7" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_03_30_page07.jpg"/>
                    
                    with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#XxxxG1">old George</persName> in the coach<lb/>
                    with him. It is 5 miles to<lb/>
                    <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#C-House_ENK">C House</placeName> from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Grove-House-Kensington-Gore_ENK">Grove house</placeName><lb/> 
                    - Yet that good <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1">Lady EW</persName> says<lb/>
                    she will often have him<lb/>
                    there - <lb/></p>
                    
                <p>  We go to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Hampstead-ENK">Hampstead</placeName> April<lb/>
                    2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. - we stay there till the<lb/>
                    14<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. More this deponent<lb/>
                    knoweth not at present<lb/></p>
                    
                <p>I enclose a letter from<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RussG1">Miss Russell.</persName><lb/></p><!-- Begin transcibing the body of the letter here. -->
                <closer>
                    Y<hi rend="superscript">s</hi> Affec<hi rend="superscript">y</hi><lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria E</persName><lb/><!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>Thank you for the account<lb/>
                        of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Saffron-Walden-Castle_ENK">Saffron Castle</placeName> and thank<lb/>
                        <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BxxxW1">William B</persName> for it - It just<lb/>
                        comes in the nick of time - I<lb/>
                        am writing to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SpenL1">Lady Spencer</persName><lb/>
                        to say I will bring <add>little</add> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Francis</persName> to<lb/>
                        see her tomorrow as she desired<lb/>
                        I rejoice that you have<lb/>
                        had your dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RussJ1">father</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BedfG1">mother</persName><lb/>
                        and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HamiL1">Louisa</persName>. Assure <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HamiL1">Louisa</persName><lb/>
                        that I do not forget, but have<lb/>
                        
                        <pb n="7" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_03_30_page07.jpg"/>
                        
                        not yet been able to get the<lb/>
                        materials for the mock <unclear>blond</unclear><lb/>
                        work I promised her.<lb/></p>
                        
                   <p>  I am very very glad to hear<lb/>
                        that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH2">Harriet Beaufort</persName> is better<lb/>
                        - I am in an agony because<lb/>
                        I have not had time to write<lb/>
                        to her - but it is impossible<lb/>
                        <del>We saw</del><lb/>
                        Ask <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">Harriet E</persName> to send me my<lb/>
                        <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">fathers</persName> translation of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StaeA1">Madame<lb/>
                            de Stael's</persName> lines and his<lb/>
                        sonnet on sickness - I have<lb/>
                        left my book at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Byrkley-Lodge_ENK">Byrkley Lodge</placeName><lb/>
                        &amp; it is easier to get the lines<lb/>
                        from <placeName ref="./Placeograhy.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworthstown</placeName> than<lb/>
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Byrkley-Lodge_ENK">B Lodge</placeName> - because the book is<lb/>
                        packed up.<lb/></p>
                        
                    <p> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BxxxG1">George B</persName> is very well &amp; looks<lb/>
                        so fat &amp; young <persName ref="./SneyX1">Sneyd</persName> scarcely<lb/>
                        knew him &amp; we fear <unclear><persName ref="./Personography.xml#XxxxM1">Molly</persName></unclear><lb/>
                        will not know him again<lb/></p>
                        
                    <p> You ought to have paid<lb/>
                        yourself various sums out<lb/>
                        of the draft you have sent me<lb/></p>
                        
                     <p>Pray send me commis-<lb/>
                        sions - I have executed all yours<lb/>
                        &amp; will find time for all <hi rend="superscript">you</hi>want<lb/>
                        
                        <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_03_30_page05.jpg"/>
                        
                        <add>- you who <hi rend="underline">make</hi>time for y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>friends</add><lb/></p>
